title: Manhunt underway in Sydney after stabbing attack kills one and injures two others
description: A stabbing attack in Western Sydney has left one person dead and two others in a critical condition.  The incident occurred on Memorial Avenue in Merrylands just after 10am Tuesday morning.  A crime scene has been established, and a manhunt for the attacker is underway.

title: ISIS-linked women seeking Australian passports pose ‘serious security risk’
description: Liberal Senator Sarah Henderson warns that ISIS-linked women seeking Australian passports to return from Syria could pose a “serious security and safety risk”.

title: Coalition will ‘never go far enough’ against ISIS brides issue: Hanson
description: One Nation Leader Pauline Hanson says the Liberal Party will never go far enough in addressing ISIS brides.  “Angus Taylor wants to appear as if, right, I am in tune with the Australian people,” Ms Hanson told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “He will never go far enough.”

title: UK aircraft company seeking base in Northern Territory
description: A British-based company has its sights on the Northern Territory as it seeks to create a second base for its stratospheric aircraft.  The so-called stratocraft can fly at an altitude of up to 70,000 feet and remain airborne for 100 days.  The stratocraft uses solar panels to constantly recharge, allowing it to stay airborne for over three months.

title: ‘Deeply troubling’: Barack Obama responds to Trump’s controversial video
description: Former US president Barack Obama has responded to the controversial video posted to Donald Trump’s Truth Social account which depicted him and his wife as apes.  Mr Obama gave his response in a recent wide-ranging podcast interview over the weekend.  President Trump removed the video after it sparked controversy and said he didn’t watch the clip until the end as he blamed the mistake on a staff member.

title: Horror shooting in Rhode Island leaves at least three dead following ‘family dispute’
description: A shooting in Rhode Island has left at least three people dead and another three in critical condition in what police are labelling a “family dispute”.  The shooting took place in the city of Pawtucket, Rhode Island, during a high school hockey game.  During a press conference following the shooting, Pawtucket Police Chief Tina Goncalves revealed the incident may have been a “family-related” matter.  “It appears that this was a targeted event, that it may be a family dispute. We cannot release the names of the victims because obviously, we want to speak to the family, make sure that the family is well aware of what happened before we release that information publicly,” Goncalves said.

title: Starmer looking at Australian-style social media ban for teens
description: The UK is deciding whether to restrict infinite scrolling as part of a plan aimed at keeping children safe online.  Prime Minister Keir Starmer also says he’s open-minded about a possible Australian-style social media ban.  “We threatened action, and we won that battle in relation to Grok, but we’ve got to do it with all AI bots,” Mr Starmer said.

title: ISIS brides from Northern Syria apply for Australian passports
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson says the families of ISIS terrorists in Northern Syria have applied for Australian passports.   “Now we learn in the Sunday Telegraph that the families of ISIS terrorists in Northern Syria have applied for Australian passports,” Ms Markson said.  “This relaxed attitude isn't good enough.”

title: Barack Obama clarifies comments about aliens after receiving global attention
description: Former US president Barack Obama has clarified his comment about aliens after he appeared to suggest they exist in a podcast interview.  “They’re real, but I haven’t seen them, and they’re not being kept in ... Area 51. There’s no underground facility unless there’s this enormous conspiracy and they hid it from the president of the United States,” he said.  The former president’s remarks received global attention over the weekend.  He has now clarified his comments in a statement on Instagram, saying: “I was trying to stick with the spirit of the speed round, but since it’s gotten attention, let me clarify.  “Statistically, the universe is so vast that the odds are good there’s life out there. But the distances between solar systems are so great that the chances we’ve been visited by aliens is low, and I saw no evidence during my presidency that extraterrestrials have made contact with us. Really.”

title: ‘Talking from personal experience’: Obama’s aliens comment sends social media into a frenzy
description: Astrophysicist and cosmologist Brad Tucker discusses former US president Barack Obama’s comment about aliens after he appeared to suggest they exist in a podcast interview.  “I think partly he was talking from personal experience,” he told Sky News Australia.  “I think if he really did see evidence, either way, he wouldn’t release it in a random podcast.”  Mr Tucker suggested aliens do exist, but the likelihood of extraterrestrials contacting Earth is low.

title: Dope of the Day: UK Amazon delivery driver gets stuck in water after following GPS instructions
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond has reacted to a UK Amazon delivery driver who drove their van into water after following GPS instructions.  “I’m sorry, does it not sort of occur to you when you’re driving down that little path directly towards a river that maybe this is not where I should be,” he said.  “And what I’m then more confused about is that clearly when he got there, it was not high tide – how long has he sat there in the van before the tide comes in?”

title: ‘We are not repatriating them’: Albanese continues to ‘monitor’ ISIS brides
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese weighs in on the ISIS brides and their families attempting to return to Australia.  This comes as 11 ISIS-linked Australian families were reportedly returned to a Syrian camp after attempting to make their way to Australia.  “We monitor all of these issues, but we are not repatriating these people,” Mr Albanese said.  “We are not repatriating them.”

title: ‘Obama, share your knowledge’: Former US president’s aliens comment ignites heated debate
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond has commented on former US president Barack Obama’s comment about aliens after he appeared to suggest they exist in a recent interview.  “How do you know? How do you know that there are aliens?” he said.  “That’s what I want to know. What evidence do they have somewhere in the US government that says aliens exist?  “I suspect they’re not little green men who are going to come down in flying saucers and try to probe you, but surely there is some kind of life form somewhere else in the universe.  “Obama, share your knowledge. You owe it to all of us to tell us.”

title: ‘They don’t want the consequences’: Trump’s warning to Iran ahead of negotiations
description: United States President Donald Trump discusses the potential for a deal with Iran as a second round of negotiations is set to take place.   “We could have had a deal instead of sending in the B2’s to knock out their nuclear potential,” Mr Trump said.   “They want to make a deal; I don’t think they want the consequences of not making a deal.”

title: Trump blasts Newsom’s UK energy pact as ‘inappropriate’, sending warning to foreign leaders
description: US President Donald Trump has sharply criticised California Governor Gavin Newsom’s clean energy agreement with the United Kingdom.  He called the deal “inappropriate” and urged foreign leaders not to partner with him.  Trump told Politico that the UK has got “enough trouble without getting involved with Gavin Newscum.”  The scathing remarks came after Newsom signed cooperation memoranda with the UK and Ukraine during his European diplomacy tour.  The moves have stoked speculation about a possible 2028 presidential bid.
